text:
Quick Facts About the Flu:

There are 16 different hemagglutinin subtypes and 9 different neuraminidase subtypes. The current subtypes of influenza A viruses circulating widely among humans are A (H1N1) and A(H3N2).

Visit us at https://t.co/ejq5rvUxKE

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Influenza A viruses are further divided into subtypes based on two viral surface glycoproteins: the hemagglutinin (H) and the neuraminidase (N).

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Humans are normally infected by human influenza viruses (H3N2, H1N1 and B) and form the primary reservoir for these human viruses.

Visit us at https://t.co/ejq5rvUxKE

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Three types of seasonal influenza viruses viruses are recognized: A, B, and C.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Only influenza A and influenza B viruses are included in seasonal influenza vaccines.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Influenza may be clinically indistinguishable from disease caused by other respiratory viruses, such as rhinovirus, RSV, parainfluenza, adenovirus, and other pathogens.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Seasonal Influenza is characterized by fever, cough (usually dry), headache, myalgia, prostration, coryza, and sore throat.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Although seasonal influenza deaths can occur in any age group, over 90% of influenza deaths occur among those aged 65 years and older.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Secondary complications of influenza also include Reye syndrome in association with use of Salicylates.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

Secondary complications of influenza include bacterial pneumonia, including co-infection with MRSA and S. pneumonia; viral pneumonia; worsening of underlying conditions; sinusitis; otitis media; febrile seizures; encephalitis/encephalopathy; myositis.

Quick Facts About the Flu:

In children, gastrointestinal (GI) manifestation (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea) may accompany the respiratory phase and have been reported in up to 25% of children in school outbreaks of influenza B and A (H1N1). GI manifestation are uncommon in adults.
